{"title_page": "The Last Train from Madrid", "text_new": "{{short description|1937 film by James P. Hogan}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Last Train from Madrid\n| caption        = \n| image          = File:The Last Train from Madrid.jpg\n| director       = [[James P. Hogan (director)|James P. Hogan]]\n| producer       = George M. Arthur\n| screenplay        = [[Louis Stevens (writer)|Louis Stevens]]<br>[[Robert Wyler]]\n| based on        = Paul Hervey Fox<br>[[Elsie Fox]]\n| starring       = [[Dorothy Lamour]]<br>[[Lew Ayres]]<br>[[Gilbert Roland]]\n| cinematography = [[Harry Fischbeck]]\n| editing        = [[Everett Douglas]]\n| studio         = Paramount Pictures\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = November 6, 1937\n| runtime        = 85 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''The Last Train from Madrid''''' is a 1937 American [[war film|war]] [[drama film]] directed by [[James P. Hogan (director)|James P. Hogan]] and starring [[Dorothy Lamour]], [[Lew Ayres]] and [[Gilbert Roland]]. It is set during the [[Spanish Civil War]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/80953/The-Last-Train-from-Madrid/ ''The Last Train from Madrid''] at [[TCMDB]]</ref> The film was one of the few contemporary [[Hollywood]] films made about the war.<ref>Schindler p.191</ref>\n\n==Production==\nLike another film about the Spanish Civil War being made at this time, ''[[Love Under Fire]]'' the filmmakers were careful not to take sides. Paramount executives described it as a \"sort of a ''[[Grand Hotel (1932 film)|Grand Hotel]]'' theme\".<ref>Spanish War to Be Basis of Two Films: Studios Use Care to Avoid Taking Sides.\nShaffer, George. Chicago Daily Tribune 09 Apr 1937: 24. </ref> The production had a number of issues with the [[Hays Office]] due to the political aspects of the subject.<ref>Schindler p.191</ref> Filming took place in April and May 1937.<ref>No More Trailers For Bob Cummings\nThe Washington Post 23 May 1937: TR1. </ref> It was mainly shot at Paramount's studios and at the [[Iverson Ranch]], although some secondary [[location shooting]] took place in [[Palencia]] in [[Castile and Le\u00f3n|Castille]]. The sets were designed by the [[art director]]s [[A. Earl Hedrick|Earl Hedrick]] and [[Hans Dreier]].\n\nIn a review the ''[[New York Times]]'' suggested that it should not be regarded too seriously. \"True, it treats of the Spanish Revolution, but merely as Hollywood has in the past regarded the turmoils of [[Ruritania]] and [[The Prisoner of Zenda|Zenda]]\".<ref>Schindler p.191</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe story of seven people: their lives and love affairs in Madrid during the Civil War.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[Dorothy Lamour]] as Carmelita Castillo\n* [[Lew Ayres]] as Bill Dexter\n* [[Gilbert Roland]] as Eduardo de Soto\n* [[Karen Morley]] as Helene Rafitto\n* [[Lionel Atwill]] as Colonel Vigo\n* [[Helen Mack]] as Lola\n* [[Robert Cummings]] as Juan Ramos\n* [[Olympe Bradna]] as Maria Ronda\n* [[Anthony Quinn]] as Captain Ricardo Alvarez\n* [[Lee Bowman]] as Michael Balk\n* [[Francis Ford]] as Pedro Elias\n* [[Alan Ladd]] as Soldier \n* [[Evelyn Brent]] as Woman soldier\n* [[Jack Perrin]] as Guard\n* [[Robert Emmett O'Connor]] as Secret Service Man\n* [[Louis Natheaux ]] as Headwaiter\n* [[Rollo Lloyd]] as Hernandez\n* [[Nigel De Brulier ]] as Philosopher \n* [[Gordon De Main]] as Gonzalez\n* [[Louise Carter]] as Rosa Delgado \n* [[Maurice Cass]] as Waiter\n* [[Hooper Atchley]] as Martin\n* [[Francis McDonald]] as Mora\n* [[George MacQuarrie ]] as Driver \n* [[Carl Harbaugh]] as Militiaman \n* [[Otto Hoffman]] as Fernando\n* [[Stanley Fields (actor)|Stanley Fields]] Avila\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Schindler, Colin. ''Hollywood in Crisis: Cinema and American Society 1929-1939''. Routledge, 2005.\n* Kear, Lynn & King, James. ''Evelyn Brent: The Life and Films of Hollywood's Lady Crook''. McFarland & Co, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0029119}}\n*[http://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-last-train-from-madrid ''The Last Train from Madrid''] at Time out\n*{{AllRovi movie|98811|The Last Train from Madrid}}\n*{{tcmdb title|80953|The Last Train from Madrid}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last Train from Madrid}}\n[[Category:1937 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Patrick Hogan]]\n[[Category:Spanish Civil War films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:1930s war drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Madrid]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n\n{{1930s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1937 film by James P. Hogan}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Last Train from Madrid\n| caption        = \n| image          = File:The Last Train from Madrid.jpg\n| director       = [[James P. Hogan (director)|James P. Hogan]]\n| producer       = George M. Arthur\n| screenplay        = [[Louis Stevens (writer)|Louis Stevens]]<br>[[Robert Wyler]]\n| based on        = Paul Hervey Fox<br>[[Elsie Fox]]\n| starring       = [[Dorothy Lamour]]<br>[[Lew Ayres]]<br>[[Gilbert Roland]]\n| cinematography = [[Harry Fischbeck]]\n| editing        = [[Everett Douglas]]\n| studio         = Paramount Pictures\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = November 6, 1937\n| runtime        = 85 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''The Last Train from Madrid''''' is a 1937 American [[war film|war]] [[drama film]] directed by [[James P. Hogan (director)|James P. Hogan]] and starring [[Dorothy Lamour]], [[Lew Ayres]] and [[Gilbert Roland]]. It is set during the [[Spanish Civil War]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/80953/The-Last-Train-from-Madrid/ ''The Last Train from Madrid''] at [[TCMDB]]</ref> The film was one of the few contemporary [[Hollywood]] films made about the war.<ref>Schindler p.191</ref>\n\n==Production==\nLike another film about the Spanish Civil War being made at this time, ''[[Love Under Fire]]'' the filmmakers were careful not to take sides. Paramount executives described it as a \"sort of a ''[[Grand Hotel (1932 film)|Grand Hotel]]'' theme\".<ref>Spanish War to Be Basis of Two Films: Studios Use Care to Avoid Taking Sides.\nShaffer, George. Chicago Daily Tribune 09 Apr 1937: 24. </ref> The production had a number of issues with the [[Hays Office]] due to the political aspects of the subject.<ref>Schindler p.191</ref> Filming took place in April and May 1937.<ref>No More Trailers For Bob Cummings\nThe Washington Post 23 May 1937: TR1. </ref> It was mainly shot at Paramount's studios and at the [[Iverson Ranch]], although some secondary [[location shooting]] took place in [[Palencia]] in [[Castille]]. The sets were designed by the [[art director]]s [[A. Earl Hedrick|Earl Hedrick]] and [[Hans Dreier]].\n\nIn a review the ''[[New York Times]]'' suggested that it should not be regarded too seriously. \"True, it treats of the Spanish Revolution, but merely as Hollywood has in the past regarded the turmoils of [[Ruritania]] and [[The Prisoner of Zenda|Zenda]]\".<ref>Schindler p.191</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe story of seven people: their lives and love affairs in Madrid during the Civil War.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[Dorothy Lamour]] as Carmelita Castillo\n* [[Lew Ayres]] as Bill Dexter\n* [[Gilbert Roland]] as Eduardo de Soto\n* [[Karen Morley]] as Helene Rafitto\n* [[Lionel Atwill]] as Colonel Vigo\n* [[Helen Mack]] as Lola\n* [[Robert Cummings]] as Juan Ramos\n* [[Olympe Bradna]] as Maria Ronda\n* [[Anthony Quinn]] as Captain Ricardo Alvarez\n* [[Lee Bowman]] as Michael Balk\n* [[Francis Ford]] as Pedro Elias\n* [[Alan Ladd]] as Soldier \n* [[Evelyn Brent]] as Woman soldier\n* [[Jack Perrin]] as Guard\n* [[Robert Emmett O'Connor]] as Secret Service Man\n* [[Louis Natheaux ]] as Headwaiter\n* [[Rollo Lloyd]] as Hernandez\n* [[Nigel De Brulier ]] as Philosopher \n* [[Gordon De Main]] as Gonzalez\n* [[Louise Carter]] as Rosa Delgado \n* [[Maurice Cass]] as Waiter\n* [[Hooper Atchley]] as Martin\n* [[Francis McDonald]] as Mora\n* [[George MacQuarrie ]] as Driver \n* [[Carl Harbaugh]] as Militiaman \n* [[Otto Hoffman]] as Fernando\n* [[Stanley Fields (actor)|Stanley Fields]] Avila\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Schindler, Colin. ''Hollywood in Crisis: Cinema and American Society 1929-1939''. Routledge, 2005.\n* Kear, Lynn & King, James. ''Evelyn Brent: The Life and Films of Hollywood's Lady Crook''. McFarland & Co, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0029119}}\n*[http://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-last-train-from-madrid ''The Last Train from Madrid''] at Time out\n*{{AllRovi movie|98811|The Last Train from Madrid}}\n*{{tcmdb title|80953|The Last Train from Madrid}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last Train from Madrid}}\n[[Category:1937 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Patrick Hogan]]\n[[Category:Spanish Civil War films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:1930s war drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Madrid]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n\n{{1930s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCastile(link changed toCastile and Le\u00f3n) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Last_Train_from_Madrid"}
{"title_page": "Mostar Airport", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Mostar International Airport\n| nativename   = {{small|Me\u0111unarodna zra\u010dna luka Mostar}}\n| image        = Mostar International Airport (logo).PNG\n| image-width  = 150\n| image2       = OMO4.jpg\n| image2-width = 250\n| IATA         = OMO\n| ICAO         = LQMO\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = City of Mostar (88%)<br />Zagreb Airport (12%)\n| operator     = Mostar Airport Ltd.\n| city-served  = [[Mostar]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| location     = [[Ortije\u0161]]\n| elevation-f  = 156\n| elevation-m  = 48\n| coordinates  = {{coord|43|16|58|N|17|50|45|E|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = [http://www.mostar-airport.ba/ mostar-airport.ba]\n| pushpin_map            = Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| pushpin_label          = OMO\n| pushpin_map_alt        =\n| pushpin_mapsize        =\n| pushpin_image          =\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location within Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| metric-elev  = Y\n| metric-rwy   = Y\n| r1-number    = 16/34\n| r1-length-f  = 7,874\n| r1-length-m  = 2,400\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year = 2019\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = '''32.866''' {{increase}} 15,4%\n| stat2-header = Aircraft Movements\n| stat2-data = '''738''' {{decrease}} 1,2%\n| stat3-header = Freight (in tons)\n| stat3-data = '''0''' {{decrease}} 0%\n| footnotes    = Source: Bosnian and Herzegovinian Directorate of Civil Aviation BHDCA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flyingbosnian.blogspot.com/2019/01/bosnia-and-herzegovina-air-traffic.html|title=Bosnia and Herzegovina aviation news: \u2708Bosnia and Herzegovina air traffic report for 2018|first=Flying|last=Bosnian|date=18 January 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Mostar International Airport''' ({{lang-hr|Me\u0111unarodna zra\u010dna luka Mostar}}; {{airport codes|OMO|LQMO|p=n}}) is an [[airport]] near [[Mostar]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], situated in the village of [[Ortije\u0161]], {{convert|4|NM|abbr=on|lk=in}} southeast of Mostar's railway station.<ref name=\"AIP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ead.eurocontrol.int/publicuser/protect/pu/main.jsp|title=EAD Basic - Error Page|publisher=|accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMostar Airport was opened for civilian air traffic in 1965 for domestic flights. Prior to 1965, Mostar was a local airport with a large concrete runway used by aircraft manufacturer [[SOKO]] for testing and delivering military aircraft, and sometimes by passenger aircraft. {{citation needed|date=February 2018}} Currently, the airport primarily serves for Catholics making the pilgrimage to nearby [[Medjugorje]]. In 2012, the airport had a twofold increase in traffic, making it the second-busiest in Bosnia and Herzegovina after [[Sarajevo International Airport|Sarajevo]] airport.\n\nFurther investments are planned, which include: renovating and expanding the terminal building, expanding the apron, modernising equipment, possible expanding of runway and further education of airport staff in Italy, also building fuel tanks and hangars for private aircraft and for aircraft of the Secondary Traffic school of Mostar which uses the airport for flight school and educating students for future work. Mostar International Airport is considering a possible strategic partnership with investors or, alternatively, a privatisation or concession.\n\nIn November 2017, [[Eurowings]] was the first airline to schedule regular  flights from Mostar to D\u00fcsseldorf and Stuttgart with two weekly flights from May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flyingbosnian.blogspot.com/2017/11/eurowings-mostar-flight-schedule.html|title=Bosnia and Herzegovina aviation news: \u2708Eurowings Mostar flight schedule|first=Flying|last=Bosnian|date=7 November 2017|publisher=}}</ref> On 3 May 2018, a Croatia Airlines plane landed at Mostar Airport marking the introduction of direct two weekly Mostar-Zagreb flights<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flyingbosnian.blogspot.com/2018/05/zagreb-mostar-flights-inaugurated.html|title=Bosnia and Herzegovina aviation news: \u2708Zagreb-Mostar flights inaugurated|first=Flying|last=Bosnian|date=4 May 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Horizont]] | '''Seasonal charter:''' [[Milan Malpensa Airport|Milan\u2013Malpensa]]<ref name=\"mostar-airport.ba\">https://mostar-airport.ba/red-letenja Red letenja</ref>\n<!--\n|[[AlbaStar]] | '''Seasonal charter:''' [[Milan Malpensa Airport|Milan\u2013Malpensa]], [[Leonardo da Vinci\u2013Fiumicino Airport|Rome\u2013Fiumicino]]<ref>https://mostar-airport.ba/red-letenja Red letenja</ref> -->\n<!-- -->\n|[[Croatia Airlines]] | [[Zagreb Airport|Zagreb]]<br>'''Seasonal charter:''' [[Beirut\u2013Rafic Hariri International Airport|Beirut]]<ref name=\"mostar-airport.ba\">https://mostar-airport.ba/red-letenja Red letenja</ref>\n<!--|[[Eurowings]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[D\u00fcsseldorf Airport|D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[Stuttgart Airport|Stuttgart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurowings.com/us/discover/destinations/route-network.html|title=Route network - Discover - Eurowings|website=www.eurowings.com}}</ref>-->\n<!-- -->\n|[[FlyBosnia]] | [[Leonardo da Vinci\u2013Fiumicino Airport|Rome\u2013Fiumicino]]<br>'''Seasonal charter:''' [[Bari Karol Wojty\u0142a Airport|Bari]],<ref name=\"FlyBosnia\"/> [[Catania\u2013Fontanarossa Airport|Catania]], [[Naples International Airport|Naples]]<ref name=\"FlyBosnia\">{{cite web|url=http://flyingbosnian.blogspot.com/2019/08/flybosnia-adds-italy-mostar-charter.html|title=FlyBosnia adds Italy-Mostar charter flights|date=31 August 2019|publisher=flyingbosnian.blogspot.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://flyingbosnian.blogspot.com/2019/10/mostar-winter-2019-20.html|title=Mostar Winter 2019-20|date=25 October 2019|publisher=flyingbosnian.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n}}\n\n==Statistics==\n\nThe record number of 86.000 passengers was recorded in t