ass=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Country\n! Won\n! Runner-up\n! Total\n|-\n| 1 ||align=left| {{ITA}} || 19 || 11 || 30 \n|-\n| 2 ||align=left| {{URS}} || 7 || 2 || 9 \n|-\n| 3 ||align=left| {{RUS}} || 4 || 4 || 8\n|-\n| 4 ||align=left| {{FRA}} || 4 || 1 || 5 \n|-\n| 5 ||align=left| {{GRC}} || 2 || 4 || 6 \n|-\n| 6 ||align=left| {{TCH}} || 2 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| 7 ||align=left| {{BGR}} || 1 || 6 || 7 \n|-\n| 8 ||align=left| {{ROU}} || 1 || 4 || 5 \n|-\n| 9 ||align=left| {{TUR}} || 1 || 2 || 3 \n|-\n|rowspan=5| 10 ||align=left| {{NED}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{BEL}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{POR}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{GER}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n|align=left| {{UKR}} || 1 || 1 || 2 \n|-\n| 15 ||align=left| {{SLO}} || 1 || \u2013 || 1 \n|-\n| 16 ||align=left| {{POL}} || \u2013 || 3 || 3 \n|-\n| 17 ||align=left| {{ESP}} || \u2013 || 3 || 3\n|-\n| 18 ||align=left| {{HUN}} || \u2013 || 1 || 1 \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.cev.eu CEV Website]\n*[https://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/History.aspx?ID=1194 History of the Competition]\n\n{{CEV Cup seasons}}\n{{European Volleyball Competitions}}\n{{Professional Volleyball Leagues}}\n{{European Club Competitions}}\n{{International volleyball}}\n\n[[Category:Men's CEV Cup| ]]\n[[Category:European men's volleyball club competitions]]\n[[Category:European volleyball records and statistics]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1972]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CEV_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Anthony James (artist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anthony James\n| image              = Anthony James in Los Angeles 2015.jpg\n| caption            = Anthony James in his Los Angeles studio\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = 1974\n| birth_place        = England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British/American\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = British/American [[art]]ist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Sculpture]], [[painting]], and experiential [[installations]].\n| notable_works      = Portals, K\u0398 (Kalos Thanatos), Birch\n}}\n\n'''Anthony James''' is a British/American [[art]]ist based in Los Angeles, known for his monumental and experiential sculptures and installations. His work gestures towards the theatricality of [[minimalism]] and [[Formalism (art)|formalism]], there's a focus on materiality, alchemy, and with light and space.\n\n''\"My work is my best attempt at giving the impossible, the infinite, a physical, objective existence. The materials are merely an extension of the gesture. I start with the gesture and have spent decades distilling these concepts down to the essential. So whether I\u2019m using vanguard, illustrious materials and high technology or centuries old metal techniques \u2014 my interest is in communicating the most direct way I can. There is a minimalistic simplicity to the work, yet it expresses something infinite \u2014 it\u2019s a pluralistic paradox. I\u2019ve tried to visually demonstrate the colossally vast and the infinitesimally small \u2014 the cosmos and the divinity inside oneself.\" -Anthony James''\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAnthony James was born in [[England]] in 1974. He studied in [[London]] at [[Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design]] and graduated with a degree in fine art painting. James has also called New York City, Munich, and Los Angeles home. Currently, he is based in Los Angeles and operates his studio in Downtown LA. \n\n==Art==\n\n'''Portals / [[Plato|Platonic]] Solids / [[Archimedean solid|Archimedean]] Solids, 2008-present'''\n[[File:Anthony James Portals.jpg|thumb|[http://www.anthonyjamesstudio.com Anthony James Studio - Portals]]]\nThe sculptures, made of stainless steel, glass, and LED lights, have shown internationally to great acclaim. \n\n''\"I\u2019m interested in revealing and sharing truth. My intention is to bring an impossible concept like the idea of infinity, or the cosmos, into physical objective existence. I am attempting to express science, spirituality, and philosophy in an object the purest and most honest way I know how.\"'' \n\n'''K\u0398 Kalos Thanatos, 2008''' \n[[File:Kalos Thanatos 019 R.jpg|thumb|K\u0398 Kalos Thanatos, 2008 Anthony James]]\nJames gained international recognition in 2008 for his work Kalos Thanatos (K\u0398), Greek for \u201cbeautiful death\u201d, when he burned his [[Ferrari F355|Ferrari F335]] Spyder in a birch forest, and then displayed it in a mirrored glass box with birch tree trunks.<ref>Michael Slenske, 2017, \u201cSpiritual Gangster\u201d, Cultured Magazine, pp. 194-199.</ref> James was inspired by the ancient Greeks, who made sacrifices to [[Aphrodite]] in birch forests.<ref>Michael Slenske, 2017, \u201cSpiritual Gangster\u201d, Cultured Magazine, pp. 194-199.</ref> [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] lauded James\u2019 Kalos Thanatos by describing it as daring: \u201cI miss art going out on a limb...Just a slim limb that looks like there\u2019s at least some chance of it snapping...Anthony James burned his Ferrari and put it in a box, amid, actually, a bunch of limbs. That was going for it\u2026.this work is pretty gutsy...The car was a victim, a sacrifice old-school redux.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71</ref>\n\n'''The Birch Series, 2005-Present'''\n\nJames originally debuted The Birch Series in New York City in 2005. It consisted of several variously sized, vertical light boxes with young birch tree trunks inside. The sculpture series references the containment and simulation of nature. The works have mirrored sides, which give the illusion of an endless birch forest. The pieces are comprised of birch trees, metal, glass, and fluorescent lights or LEDs. The birch tree is associated with magical symbolism. [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] wrote about birch trees that their \u201cmagic...is rooted in [the] special relationship with fly agaric mushrooms - that famed toadstool of the red cap and white spots - which is so often associated with elves and spirits...Many anthropologists consider it to be a possible agent of the transformation of human consciousness.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> Of the series, James said, \"''I think about the containment of nature. The containment of our own nature. There\u2019s something about the individuals journey that is really at the root of it. Going into the forest \u2014 not knowing what you\u2019ll find \u2014 not knowing if you\u2019ll ever return... You can see the metaphor.\"''\n\n'''Morphic Fields, 2014'''\n\nMorphic Fields was an exhibition of bronze and limestone pieces inspired by the scientist [[Rupert Sheldrake]]\u2019s theory of morphic resonance: \u201ca process whereby self-organizing systems inherit a memory from previous similar systems.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> Sheldrake describes his theory relative to the artistic process: \u201cEvery morphic fields starts with some creative step. Newton was the first person to think of the law of gravity. And before he\u2019d thought of it, no one else had. Since then, millions of people have been able to think of it. So all morphic fields begin with individuals\u2026Very few contemporary artists have the sense of inspiration from a transcendent source beyond the human realm. But I would argue that they are also drawing from the collective human experience. As much as there is room for individual creativity, every artist is also transcending collective memory. Artists can create new morphic fields. Yet, all art exists within a morphic field beyond the individual.\u201d<ref>Katja Eichinger, \u201cAn Interview with Rupert Sheldrake\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 52-57.</ref> The sculptures are created from found materials and \u201cthrough [James\u2019] process of converting...waste into bronze they morph into something very beautiful and precious.\u201d<ref>Matthias Muhling, \u201cAn Interview with Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 77-89.</ref>\n\n'''Shields, 2016-Present'''\n\nShields was an exhibition of curved disks made of brass, bronze, and steel \u201cscarred with [[Minimalism|minimalist]] markings.\u201d This series \u201coperates elusively, staggering between the iconic and the arbitrary, the concrete and the alchemic, the mythical and experiential.\u201d<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> James describes his work as, \u201cevoking pictorial depictions of the [[cosmos]], alluding to notions of mysticism, ethereality, and science fiction, all the while anchored through the use of weighty, industrial materials such as metal.\"<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> The shields \u201cread as relics or artifacts from some liminal moment, as such, James attempts to locate beauty in the wake of insanity.\u201d<ref>Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref>\n\n'''Rain Paintings, 2018'''\n\nA photorealistic series made of contradictory materials: Belgian linen, gesso, and [https://www.ppgdeltron.com Deltron]. \u201cPurity is an illusion. The timeless, cleansing rain evoked by James\u2019 paintings is artificial. The viewer can encounter the work through a meditative fascination with its lucid intricacy \u2013 the eternal and universal behavior of water. And the aesthetic pleasure of this is intense. But to read it as only beautiful or mystical is to miss the logic of contradiction that gives the work its conceptual strength, the spray of toxic industrial paint onto an object recognizable to any old-master artist\u2019s apprentice. Therefore, in a larger sense, this work presents an argument for combination and exchange over homogeneity and conformity. James\u2019 new mode of painting can be read as a critique of easy simulation, of virtuality, in relation to both traditional illusionism and the digital. By layering contrasting material processes to create a seeming unity, a surface of streaming water, these works insist on the real over the hyperreal and on the assembled, heterogeneous, contested nature of that reality.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://there-there.co/therethere-exhibitions|title=exhibitions|website=there-there|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n'''Neons, 2002-present'''\n\nColorful rings of neon nod to the ancient concept of the universe as set of concentric planetary orbits. The effect is both esoteric and industrial, morphic and distinctly concrete.\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nSelected Solo Exhibitions\n\n* 2020: [[Opera Gallery]], London, England\n*2018: Rain Paintings, There-There Gallery, Los Angeles, CA\n*2017: Portals, There-There Gallery, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2017: Shields, [http://www.fortgansevoort.com Fort Gansevoort], New York, NY\n* 2016: Maloney Fine Art, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2014: Morphic Fields, [https://www.storms-galerie.de Walter Storms Galerie], Munich, Germany\n* 2012: Consciousness And Portraits Of Sacrifice, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2010: \u039a\u0398, Patrick Painter Gallery, Santa Monica, CA\n* 2007: Visionaire Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2007: Milk Gallery presented by [https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], New York, NY\n*2007: [https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], West Palm Beach, FL\n* 2006: Kantor/Feuer Window, New York, NY\n* 2005: Holasek Wier Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/finch/finch3-6-06.asp|title=artnet Magazine - The Return of Anthony James|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* 1999: Four, Four, Four Apex Art, New York, NY\n\nSelected Group Exhibitions\n\n* 2019: [https://crystalbridges.org/exhibitions/crystals/ Crystals In Art: Ancient to Today], [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], Bentonville, AR\n*2018: [https://www.art-aspen.com Art Aspen], Aspen, Colorado with [https://melissamorganfineart.com Melissa Morgan Fine Art]\n* 2014: [https://www.louise-alexander.com/exhibition/art-international-istanbul-2016/ Art International Istanbul], Istanbul, Turkey with [https://www.louise-alexander.com Louise Alexander Gallery]\n* 2011: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2011: The shortest distance between 2 points is often intolerable, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2011: \u201cPieces of Heaven\u201d Auction, [[The Art of Elysium]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2010: [[Art Basel]] 41, Basel, Switzerland\n* 2010: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2010: Angel Art Auction Presented by [[Creative Artists Agency|CAA]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2009: Blue, Blue, Kim Light / LightBox, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2008: Getting Out Our Dreams, Otero Plassart, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: Some Kind of Portrait, [http://www.marcselwynfineart.com Mark Selwyn], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, CA\n* 2007: [[Art Basel]], Miami, FL\n* 2006: The Monty Hall Problem, curated by [[Slater Bradley]], [[Blum & Poe|Blum and Poe]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2006: Flaming June VI, curated by Sarah Gavlak, [http://www.spaniermanmodern.com Spanierman Modern], New York, NY\n* 2006: Color Theory and Practice, Briggs Robinson Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2006: Twenty-Five Bold Moves, curated by [https://simonwatsonarts.com Simon Watson] and Craig Hensala Of Scenic, House of Campari, New York, NY\n* 2002: Superimposition, curated by [http://www.d-hunt.com/origin.html David Hunt], [https://www.carengoldenfineart.com Caren Golden Fine Art], New York, NY\n* 2000: [[New Museum|The New Museum]], curated by [http://stefanobasilico.com/cv.html Stefano Basilico], New York, NY\n* 1999: Room With A View, Sixth @ Prince Gallery, New York, NY\n*1999: Road Show, DFN Gallery, New York, NY\n* 1999: Machine Gun Etiquette, [https://spencerbrownstonegallery.com/main Spencer Brownstone Gallery], New York, NY\n* 1999: Foul Play, Thread Waxing Space, New York, NY\n\n==Publications==\n[[File:Morphic Fields Book AnthonyJames.jpg|thumb|Morphic Fields by: Anthony James]]\n''[https://www.hatjecantz.de/anthony-james-6131-1.html?article_id=6131&clang=1 Morphic Fields Book], 2014''\n\n''Morphic Fields'' is the title of a series of twenty-one amorphous bronze sculptures with limestone bases\u2014 works created from cardboard boxes dipped in and shaped with wax and subsequently cast in bronze. This first monograph on Anthony James includes a number of offbeat essays on the artist\u2019s work. Fashion and art critic [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] provided sharp-witted in\u00adsights, and writer [[Christian Kracht]] added his typically sardonic commentary. An interview with controversial biologist [[Rupert Sheldrake]] was a highly fitting contribu\u00adtion; his theory of morphic fields inspired the artist\u2019s work and the title of this publication. Other text contributions include a piece by: Matthias M\u00fchling. The book was printed in Germany and published by [https://www.hatjecantz.de Hatje Cantz Verlag].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonyjamesstudio.com Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Anthony}}\n[[Category:British sculptors]]\n[[Category:British male sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:Postmodern artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Central Saint Martins]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anthony James\n| image              = Anthony James in Los Angeles 2015.jpg\n| caption            = Anthony James in his Los Angeles studio\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = 1974\n| birth_place        = England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British/American\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = British/American [[art]]ist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Sculpture]], [[painting]], and [[installations]]\n| notable_works      = Portal Icosahedron, K\u0398 (Kalos Thanatos), Birch\n}}\n\n'''Anthony James''' is a British/American [[art]]ist based in Los Angeles, known for his monumental and performative sculptures and installations. His work gestures towards [[minimalism]], materiality, process, alchemy, language, mechanization, and experimentation with light and space. [http://www.michaelslenske.com/about Michael Slenske] interviewed James about his art. Slenske said \u201cThough he claims a lot of his art is about esoteric concerns, death and rebirth, and a certain spiritual energy, he also argues, \u2018A lot of the art is in the correction of a mistake or maybe it is the mistake. I\u2019m very open to what comes to me. I feel like certain things are serendipitous.\u2019\u201d<ref>Michael Slenske, 2017, \u201cSpiritual Gangster\u201d, Cultured Magazine, pp. 194-199.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAnthony James was born in [[England]] in 1974. He studied in [[London]] at [[Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design]] from 1994 to 1998 and graduated with a degree in fine art painting. In 1998, he moved to New York City and ten years later to Los Angeles. He did a brief stint in Munich for two years starting in 2013 and then moved back to Los Angeles. \n\n==Art==\n\n'''Portals/Icosahedrons, 2011-present'''\n\nThe Portals/Icosahedrons are made from titanium, LED lights, and [[transparent mirror]]s.<ref>https://craftcouncil.org/post/five-highlights-sofa-2018</ref> Art historian Rachel Baum wrote about the show that \u201cAnthony James\u2019 work takes up the concepts of the universal and transcendental in order to demonstrate the impossibility of their representation. The historical [[cosmology]] of [[Plato]] is a primary inspiration, both for the sculptures of icosahedrons and for the silhouette of [[Baroque]] architecture [[Francesco Borromini]]\u2019s dome for [[Sant'Ivo alla Sapienza|Sant\u2019Ivo]] in [[Rome]]. \n\n'''Neons, 2010-present'''\n\nColorful rings of neon nod to the ancient concept of the universe as set of concentric planetary orbits. The effect is both esoteric and industrial, morphic and distinctly concrete.\u201d The works have a \u201cspectra of colored neon tubes arranged in concentric circles to evoke the radiance of sacred enlightenment. The hue and intensity of the colors are designed to create white light. The historical references here span empirical experimentation with prisms to the image, across cultures, of the universe-wheel. [[Neon]] is already in our time a somewhat outworn material and the visible wires and plugs that trail from the vibrant rings interrupt any illusions of transcendence. This is the paradox that James\u2019 objects show, a formal certainty and perspicuity (exact symmetry, white light, accurate shape) that registers a loss of purity or autonomy or wholeness. His works illustrate ideals, but they themselves are very contingent and actual, particular, not universal: they are for today.\u201d\n\n'''Shields, 2016'''\n\nShields was an exhibition of curved disks made of brass, bronze, and steel with \u201cscarred with [[Minimalism|minimalist]] markings.\u201d This series \u201coperates elusively, staggering between the iconic and the arbitrary, the concrete and the alchemic, the mythical and experiential.\u201d<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> James describes his work as, \u201cevoking pictorial depictions of the [[cosmos]], alluding to notions of mysticism, ethereality, and science fiction, all the while anchored through the use of weighty, industrial materials such as metal.\"<ref> Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref> The shields \u201cread as relics or artifacts from some liminal moment, as such, James attempts to locate beauty in the wake of insanity.\u201d<ref>Fort Gansevoort, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55ee2fc1e4b0c1020ff7e01a/t/591f29c103596e77e94503c7/1495214536115/FG_AnthonyJames_PressRelease_FINAL.pdf, \u201cAnthony James/Fabulism\u201d, 2017.</ref>\n\n'''Morphic Fields, 2014'''\n\nMorphic Fields is an exhibition of bronze and limestone pieces inspired by the scientist [[Rupert Sheldrake]]\u2019s theory of morphic resonance: \u201ca process whereby self-organizing systems inherit a memory from previous similar systems.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> Sheldrake describes his theory relative to the artistic process: \u201cEvery morphic fields starts with some creative step. Newton was the first person to think of the law of gravity. And before he\u2019d thought of it, no one else had. Since then, millions of people have been able to think of it. So all morphic fields begin with individuals\u2026Very few contemporary artists have the sense of inspiration from a transcendent source beyond the human realm. But I would argue that they are also drawing from the collective human experience. As much as there is room for individual creativity, every artist is also transcending collective memory. Artists can create new morphic fields. Yet, all art exists within a morphic field beyond the individual.\u201d<ref>Katja Eichinger, \u201cAn Interview with Rupert Sheldrake\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 52-57.</ref> The sculptures are created from found materials and \u201cthrough [James\u2019] process of converting...waste into bronze they morph into something very beautiful and precious.\u201d<ref>Matthias Muhling, \u201cAn Interview with Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 77-89.</ref>\n\n'''Kalos Thanatos, 2008'''\n\nJames gained international recognition in 2008 for his work Kalos Thanatos (KO), Greek for \u201cbeautiful death\u201d, when he burned his [[Ferrari F355|Ferrari F335]] Spyder in a birch forest, and then displayed it in a mirrored glass box with birch tree trunks.<ref>Michael Slenske, 2017, \u201cSpiritual Gangster\u201d, Cultured Magazine, pp. 194-199.</ref> James was inspired by the ancient Greeks, who burned sacrifices to [[Aphrodite]] in birch forests.<ref>Michael Slenske, 2017, \u201cSpiritual Gangster\u201d, Cultured Magazine, pp. 194-199.</ref> [[Glenn O'Brien|O\u2019Brien]] lauded James\u2019 Kalos Thanatos by describing it as daring: \u201cI miss art going out on a limb...Just a slim limb that looks like there\u2019s at least some chance of it snapping...Anthony James burned his Ferrari and put it in a box, amid, actually, a bunch of limbs. That was going for it\u2026.this work is pretty gutsy...The car was a victim, a sacrifice old-school redux.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71</ref>\n\n'''Birch Series, 2005-Present'''\n\nBirch Series is a series of sculptures James debuted in New York City in 2005. They consist of several variously sized, vertical light boxes with young birch tree trunks inside.<ref>Designboom.com, https://www.designboom.com/art/anthony-james-birch-at-design-miami-basel-2010/, Andrea Chin, \u201cAnthony James \u2018Birch\u2019 at Design Miam Basel 2010\u201d, 2010.</ref> The birch tree is associated with magical symbolism: [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] wrote about birch trees that there \u201cmagic...is rooted in [the] special relationship with fly agaric mushrooms - that famed toadstool of the red cap and white spots - which is so often associated with elves and spirits...Many anthropologists consider it to be a possible agent of the transformation of human consciousness.\u201d<ref>Designboom.com, https://www.designboom.com/art/anthony-james-birch-at-design-miami-basel-2010/, Andrea Chin, \u201cAnthony James \u2018Birch\u2019 at Design Miam Basel 2010\u201d, 2010.</ref> The birch tree is also \u201cassociated with birth and rebirth\u201d and is \u201chermaphroditic and self-propagating, with male and female flowers on the same tree.\u201d<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref>  Birch was also traditionally used to discipline students in schools.<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> The works have mirrored sides, which give the illusion of endless birch forests.<ref>Glenn O\u2019Brien, \u201cCasual Magic: The Art of Anthony James\u201d, Morphic Fields, Munich: Hatje Cantz Verlag, 2014, pp. 58-71.</ref> The pieces are made out of Minnesotan birch trees, aluminum, glass, and fluorescent lights or LEDs.<ref>Designboom.com, https://www.designboom.com/art/anthony-james-birch-at-design-miami-basel-2010/, Andrea Chin, \u201cAnthony James \u2018Birch\u2019 at Design Miami Basel 2010\u201d, 2010.</ref> Birch Series also references the containment and simulation of nature.\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nSolo Exhibitions\n\n* 2020: [[Opera Gallery]], London, England\n*2017: Portals, There-There Gallery, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2017: Shields, [http://www.fortgansevoort.com Fort Gansevoort], New York, NY\n* 2016: Maloney Fine Art, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2014: Morphic Fields, [https://www.storms-galerie.de Walter Storms Galerie], Munich, Germany\n* 2012: Consciousness And Portraits Of Sacrifice, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2010: \u039a\u0398, Patrick Painter Gallery, Santa Monica, CA\n* 2007: Visionaire Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2007: Milk Gallery presented by [https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], New York, NY\n*[https://www.gavlakgallery.com/gallery Gavlak], West Palm Beach, FL\n* 2006: Kantor/Feuer Window, New York, NY\n* 2005: Holasek Wier Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/finch/finch3-6-06.asp|title=artnet Magazine - The Return of Anthony James|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* 1999: Four, Four, Four Apex Art, New York, NY\n\nGroup Exhibitions\n\n* 2019: [https://crystalbridges.org/exhibitions/crystals/ Crystals In Art: Ancient to Today], [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], Bentonville, AR\n*2018: [https://www.art-aspen.com Art Aspen], Aspen, Colorado with [https://melissamorganfineart.com Melissa Morgan Fine Art]\n* 2014: [https://www.louise-alexander.com/exhibition/art-international-istanbul-2016/ Art International Istanbul], Istanbul, Turkey with [https://www.louise-alexander.com Louise Alexander Gallery]\n* 2011: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2011: The shortest distance between 2 points is often intolerable, [http://www.brandnew-gallery.com/Software/ Brand New Gallery], Milan, Italy\n* 2011: \u201cPieces of Heaven\u201d Auction, [[The Art of Elysium]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2010: [[Art Basel]] 41, Basel, Switzerland\n* 2010: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, NY\n* 2010: Angel Art Auction Presented by [[Creative Artists Agency|CAA]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2009: Blue, Blue, Kim Light / LightBox, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2008: Getting Out Our Dreams, Otero Plassart, Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: Some Kind of Portrait, [http://www.marcselwynfineart.com Mark Selwyn], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2007: [[The Armory Show (art fair)|The Armory Show]], New York, CA\n* 2007: [[Art Basel]], Miami, FL\n* 2006: The Monty Hall Problem, curated by [[Slater Bradley]], [[Blum & Poe|Blum and Poe]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2006: Flaming June VI, curated by Sarah Gavlak, [http://www.spaniermanmodern.com Spanierman Modern], New York, NY\n* 2006: Color Theory and Practice, Briggs Robinson Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2006: Twenty-Five Bold Moves, curated by [https://simonwatsonarts.com Simon Watson] and Craig Hensala Of Scenic, House of Campari, New York, NY\n* 2002: Superimposition, curated by [http://www.d-hunt.com/origin.html David Hunt], [https://www.carengoldenfineart.com Caren Golden Fine Art], New York, NY\n* 2000: [[New Museum|The New Museum]], curated by [http://stefanobasilico.com/cv.html Stefano Basilico], New York, NY\n* 1999: Room With A View, Sixth @ Prince Gallery, New York, NY\n*1999: Road Show, DFN Gallery, New York, NY\n* 1999: Machine Gun Etiquette, [https://spencerbrownstonegallery.com/main Spencer Brownstone Gallery], New York, NY\n* 1999: Foul Play, Thread Waxing Space, New York, NY\n\n==Publications==\n\n''[https://www.hatjecantz.de/anthony-james-6131-1.html?article_id=6131&clang=1 Morphic Fields Book], 2014''\n\n''Morphic Fields'' is the title of a series of twenty-one amorphous bronze sculptures with limestone bases\u2014 works created from cardboard boxes dipped in and shaped with wax and subsequently cast in bronze. This first monograph on Anthony James includes a number of offbeat essays on the artist\u2019s work. Fashion and art critic [[Glenn O'Brien|Glenn O\u2019Brien]] provided sharp-witted in\u00adsights, and writer [[Christian Kracht]] added his typically sardonic commentary. An interview with controversial biologist [[Rupert Sheldrake]] was a highly fitting contribu\u00adtion; his theory of morphic fields inspired the artist\u2019s work and the title of this publication. Other text contributions include pieces by [[Katja Eichinger]] and Matthias M\u00fchling. The book was printed in Germany and published by [https://www.hatjecantz.de Hatje Cantz Verlag].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonyjamesstudio.com Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Anthony}}\n[[Category:British sculptors]]\n[[Category:British male sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century sculptors]]\n[[Category:Postmodern artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Central Saint Martins]]\n", "name_user": "InfinityDivinity", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor updates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_James_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "Wet market", "text_new": "{{Short description|Market selling perishable goods, generally including meat or food animals}}\n{{Chinese|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg|picsize=250px|c=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]|j=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>|l=street market|showflag=j|ci={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}}}\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary -->\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|Modern Asian wet markets are housed in buildings, though there are still numerous street-level wet markets throughout Asia.]]\n\nA '''wet market''' is a market selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |publisher=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market  n. South-East Asian a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce  |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Wet markets are common throughout the world.<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA LAUNCHES PETITION TO SHUT DOWN LIVE ANIMAL MARKETS THAT BREED DISEASES LIKE COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets |title= No, China\u2019s fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Christopher |last=St. Cavendish |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3412023/|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nWet markets containing live wild animals and wildlife products have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s including [[coronavirus disease 2019]], but most wet markets are not wildlife markets.<ref name=\"lat\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly wet floors as a consequence of the spraying of fresh produce and cleaning of meat and seafood stalls.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC |title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance |first=Dawn |last=Burton |page=146 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2008}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"wet market\" originated from [[Hong Kong English]] and entered the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 May 2016 |title=East Asian words make it into ''Oxford English Dictionary'' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/13/east-asian-words-oxford-english-dictionary-hong-kong-singapore-oed |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=22 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than [[supermarket]]s due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Around the world==\n=== In China ===\n[[File:Fowl cages at wet market in Shenzhen, China.jpg|thumb|Fowl cages at wet market in [[Shenzhen]], China]]\nThe origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, proposals were made to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref> A few others have pointed out that most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=Commentary: No, China\u2019s fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=2020-03-11|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese \u2018wet markets\u2019 could be a terrible mistake|last=Lynteris|first=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020. The Chinese government subsequently announced a permanent ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market.|author=Aylin Woodward}}</ref> By {{date|2020-03-28|DMY}}, wet markets were reported to have been reopened across China, leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wild animal trade by members of the U.S. government.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/coronavirus-chinese-wet-markets-still-operation-despite-covid19/news-story/104a81601ff7b94fec6dae3e158ad0a1|title=Coronavirus: Chinese wet markets still operation despite COVID-19|date=2020-03-30|work=News.com.au|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== In Hong Kong ===\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012||language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref><br />\n\nCentral Market was launched on 16 May 1842. Its position was central, on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong's wet markets use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===In Mexico===\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===In Singapore===\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref>\n\n===In Thailand===\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003}}</ref>\n\n== Hygiene of wildlife markets ==\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets containing wildlife products can spread [[disease|diseases]]. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers. Insects such as [[flies]] have relatively easy access to the food products. Carcasses are sometimes thrown on the floor to be butchered. The [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|avian flu]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human |title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human |department=Goats and Soda |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=2020-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-01-24 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nWet markets where animals are traded in unsanitary conditions combined with the ability of viruses to undergo fast recombination were pointed out as a \"time-bomb\" as early as in 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|date=Oct 2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|url=https://cmr.asm.org/content/20/4/660.long|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20(4)|pages=660-94|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Large numbers and varieties of these wild game mammals in overcrowded cages and the lack of biosecurity measures in wet markets allowed the jumping of this novel virus from animals to human. (...) Coronaviruses are well known to undergo genetic recombination, which may lead to new genotypes and outbreaks. The presence of a large reservoir of SARS-CoV-like viruses in horseshoe bats, together with the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China, is a time bomb.|author=VC Cheng|title=|source=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection}}\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been blamed for the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Don't Blame China. The Next Pandemic Could Come From Anywhere|last=|first=|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China\u2019s attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|Wet market in Tekka Center, [[Singapore]]\nImage:HK SYP Market 60402.jpg|Indoor wet market in Hong Kong\nImage:E8975-Namdaemun-ginseng-and-matsutake-shop.jpg|Live turtles next to pickled ginseng in [[Namdaemun Market]], [[Seoul]]\nImage:Lok_fu_centre_wet_market.jpg|Indoor wet market under Lok Fu Shopping Centre in Hong Kong\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Artisanal food]]\n* [[Asian supermarket]]\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Farmers' market]]\n* [[Palengke]]\n* [[Pasar malam]]\n* [[Pasar pagi]]\n* [[Souk]]\n* [[Social distancing]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|Wet markets}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/may/15/china-animalwelfare-cat | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Conservation (Environment), Wildlife (Environment), World news, China (News), Animal welfare (News), Food (impact of production on environment), Animals (News), Ethical and green living (Environment), Environment, Chinese food and drink, Asia Pacific (News) | date=15 May 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:Food markets]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n[[Category:Vegetables]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Market selling perishable goods, generally including meat or food animals}}\n{{Chinese|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg|picsize=250px|c=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]|j=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>|l=street market|showflag=j|ci={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}}}\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary -->\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|Modern Asian wet markets are housed in buildings, though there are still numerous street-level wet markets throughout Asia.]]\n\nA '''wet market''' is a market selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |publisher=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market  n. South-East Asian a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce  |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Wet markets are common throughout the world.<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA LAUNCHES PETITION TO SHUT DOWN LIVE ANIMAL MARKETS THAT BREED DISEASES LIKE COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets |title= No, China\u2019s fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Christopher |last=St. Cavendish |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3412023/|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nWet markets containing live wild animals and wildlife products have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s including [[coronavirus disease 2019]], but most wet markets are not wildlife markets.<ref name=\"lat\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly wet floors as a consequence of the spraying of fresh produce and cleaning of meat and seafood stalls.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC |title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance |first=Dawn |last=Burton |page=146 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2008}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"wet market\" originated from [[Hong Kong English]] and entered the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 May 2016 |title=East Asian words make it into ''Oxford English Dictionary'' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/13/east-asian-words-oxford-english-dictionary-hong-kong-singapore-oed |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=22 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than [[supermarket]]s due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Around the world==\n=== In China ===\n[[File:Fowl cages at wet market in Shenzhen, China.jpg|thumb|Fowl cages at wet market in [[Shenzhen]], China]]\nThe origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, proposals were made to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref> A few others have pointed out that most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=Commentary: No, China\u2019s fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=2020-03-11|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese \u2018wet markets\u2019 could be a terrible mistake|last=Lynteris|first=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020. The Chinese government subsequently announced a permanent ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market.|author=Aylin Woodward}}</ref> By {{date|2020-03-28|DMY}}, wet markets were reported to have been reopened across China, leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wild animal trade by members of the U.S. government.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Knowles|first=George|url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-8163761/Chinese-markets-selling-bats.html|title=Will they ever learn? Chinese markets are still selling bats and slaughtering rabbits on blood-soaked floors as Beijing celebrates 'victory' over the coronavirus|date=2020-03-28|work=The Daily Mail|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Hooten|first=Kyle|url=https://dailycaller.com/2020/03/29/chinese-markets-reopen-bats-dogs-cats/|title=Chinese Markets Reopen \u2014 And They Still Sell Bats, Dogs And Cats|date=2020-03-29|work=The Daily Caller|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/coronavirus-chinese-wet-markets-still-operation-despite-covid19/news-story/104a81601ff7b94fec6dae3e158ad0a1|title=Coronavirus: Chinese wet markets still operation despite COVID-19|date=2020-03-30|work=News.com.au|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== In Hong Kong ===\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012||language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref><br />\n\nCentral Market was launched on 16 May 1842. Its position was central, on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong's wet markets use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===In Mexico===\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===In Singapore===\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref>\n\n===In Thailand===\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003}}</ref>\n\n== Hygiene of wildlife markets ==\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets containing wildlife products can spread [[disease|diseases]]. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers. Insects such as [[flies]] have relatively easy access to the food products. Carcasses are sometimes thrown on the floor to be butchered. The [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|avian flu]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human |title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human |department=Goats and Soda |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=2020-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-01-24 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nWet markets where animals are traded in unsanitary conditions combined with the ability of viruses to undergo fast recombination were pointed out as a \"time-bomb\" as early as in 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|date=Oct 2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|url=https://cmr.asm.org/content/20/4/660.long|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20(4)|pages=660-94|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Large numbers and varieties of these wild game mammals in overcrowded cages and the lack of biosecurity measures in wet markets allowed the jumping of this novel virus from animals to human. (...) Coronaviruses are well known to undergo genetic recombination, which may lead to new genotypes and outbreaks. The presence of a large reservoir of SARS-CoV-like viruses in horseshoe bats, together with the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China, is a time bomb.|author=VC Cheng|title=|source=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection}}\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been blamed for the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Don't Blame China. The Next Pandemic Could Come From Anywhere|last=|first=|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China\u2019s attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|Wet market in Tekka Center, [[Singapore]]\nImage:HK SYP Market 60402.jpg|Indoor wet market in Hong Kong\nImage:E8975-Namdaemun-ginseng-and-matsutake-shop.jpg|Live turtles next to pickled ginseng in [[Namdaemun Market]], [[Seoul]]\nImage:Lok_fu_centre_wet_market.jpg|Indoor wet market under Lok Fu Shopping Centre in Hong Kong\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\